<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="32" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,314,1843]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,314,340]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
I regard the structure of the antennal flagellum (
<figureCitation box="[858,957,314,340]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–10" captionStartId="6.[151,269,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,245,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-41@6.[151,1436,194,1882]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 8–10. Panamamyia silbergliedi, gen. nov., sp. nov., male holotype. 8, dorsal view. 9, lateral view. 10, head and antennae, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107276" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107276/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Figs. 10</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[969,1000,314,340]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–13" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1925,1949]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-39@7.[151,1436,194,1901]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 11–13. Panamamyia silbergliedi, gen. nov., sp. nov., female paratype. 11, dorsal view. 12, lateral view. 13, dorsolateral view of head and antennae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107280" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107280/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">13</figureCitation>
), with the sixth flagellomere as wide or wider than the fifth, and nearly as wide as flagellomeres 1–4, as autapomorphic for this genus. Also, the moderately elongate abdomen with nearly straight, very gradually posteriorly tapering lateral margins is probably autapomorphic as well (
<figureCitation box="[490,572,442,468]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–10" captionStartId="6.[151,269,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,245,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-41@6.[151,1436,194,1882]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 8–10. Panamamyia silbergliedi, gen. nov., sp. nov., male holotype. 8, dorsal view. 9, lateral view. 10, head and antennae, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107276" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107276/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Figs. 8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[585,616,442,468]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–13" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1925,1949]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-39@7.[151,1436,194,1901]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 11–13. Panamamyia silbergliedi, gen. nov., sp. nov., female paratype. 11, dorsal view. 12, lateral view. 13, dorsolateral view of head and antennae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107280" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107280/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">11</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,314,1843]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
In the key of 
<bibRefCitation author="James, M. T. &amp; M. W. McFadden" box="[366,694,485,511]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" pagination="1 - 40" refId="ref3788" refString="James, M. T. &amp; M. W. McFadden. (1979) The Stratiomyinae (Diptera, Stratiomyidae) of Middle America. Melanderia, 32, [2] + 1 - 40." type="journal article" year="1979">James &amp; McFadden (1979)</bibRefCitation>
this genus keys to 
<taxonomicName authority="Meigen." authorityName="Meigen." box="[932,1185,485,511]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Odontomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[932,1077,485,510]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Odontomyia</emphasis>
Meigen.
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName box="[1205,1350,485,510]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Odontomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1205,1350,485,510]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Odontomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="2008" box="[215,370,528,553]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Panamamyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[215,370,528,553]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Panamamyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having a less strongly produced face, a much more slender sixth antennal flagellomere, and the abdomen less slender with more rounded margins. I regard the reduction in size of the fifth and sixth flagellomeres in 
<taxonomicName box="[348,493,613,638]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Odontomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[348,493,613,638]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Odontomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as apomorphic for that genus, a character state not found in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="2008" box="[1202,1356,613,638]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Panamamyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1202,1356,613,638]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Panamamyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="2008" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Panamamyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Panamamyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also bears some resemblence to 
<taxonomicName authority="Rondani" authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1864" box="[648,886,656,682]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Psellidotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[648,778,656,681]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Psellidotus</emphasis>
Rondani
</taxonomicName>
(formerly known as 
<taxonomicName authority="Enderlein" authorityName="Enderlein" authorityYear="1930" box="[1135,1424,656,682]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Labostigmina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1135,1296,656,681]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Labostigmina</emphasis>
Enderlein
</taxonomicName>
), but the latter has the apical antennal flagellomeres more closely associated and indistinctly separated from each other, and an abdomen similar to that noted for 
<taxonomicName box="[769,913,741,766]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Odontomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[769,913,741,766]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Odontomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="32" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,314,1843]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,350,783,809]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[366,434,784,809]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Male.</emphasis>
Head with eyes strongly holoptic (
<figureCitation box="[858,929,784,810]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–10" captionStartId="6.[151,269,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,245,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-41@6.[151,1436,194,1882]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 8–10. Panamamyia silbergliedi, gen. nov., sp. nov., male holotype. 8, dorsal view. 9, lateral view. 10, head and antennae, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107276" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107276/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
), upper frons reduced to a very narrow triangle, lower frons and face conically produced with rounded apex, and antenna inserted on dorsal part of this prominence. Ocellar tubercle slightly prominent. Gena only slightly visible in lateral view, occiput not visible in lateral view. Eye bare, ommatidia on upper two-thirds much larger than lower ones (
<figureCitation box="[1220,1307,912,938]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–10" captionStartId="6.[151,269,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,245,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-41@6.[151,1436,194,1882]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 8–10. Panamamyia silbergliedi, gen. nov., sp. nov., male holotype. 8, dorsal view. 9, lateral view. 10, head and antennae, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107276" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107276/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[159,260,954,980]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–10" captionStartId="6.[151,269,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,245,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-41@6.[151,1436,194,1882]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 8–10. Panamamyia silbergliedi, gen. nov., sp. nov., male holotype. 8, dorsal view. 9, lateral view. 10, head and antennae, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107276" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107276/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Figs. 10</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[276,306,954,980]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–13" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1925,1949]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-39@7.[151,1436,194,1901]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 11–13. Panamamyia silbergliedi, gen. nov., sp. nov., female paratype. 11, dorsal view. 12, lateral view. 13, dorsolateral view of head and antennae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107280" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107280/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">13</figureCitation>
) slender, pedicel slightly longer than scape; flagellum slender, parallel-sided with six distinct flagellomeres, fifth and sixth not strongly differentiated from preceding ones, sixth subequal to fourth, fifth about one-third length of sixth. Palpus small, cylindrical, about three times longer than its diameter, apparently one-segmented.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,314,1843]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
Thorax with subscutellum developed, thinly tomentose, and with a few upwardly-directed hairs at lower lateral corners. Scutellum (
<figureCitation box="[481,564,1168,1194]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–10" captionStartId="6.[151,269,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,245,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-41@6.[151,1436,194,1882]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 8–10. Panamamyia silbergliedi, gen. nov., sp. nov., male holotype. 8, dorsal view. 9, lateral view. 10, head and antennae, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107276" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107276/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Figs. 8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[579,608,1168,1194]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–13" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1925,1949]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-39@7.[151,1436,194,1901]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 11–13. Panamamyia silbergliedi, gen. nov., sp. nov., female paratype. 11, dorsal view. 12, lateral view. 13, dorsolateral view of head and antennae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107280" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107280/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">11</figureCitation>
) trapezoidal with two short conical spines about one-fourth length of scutellum and separated by about twice the length of one spine. Legs unremarkable, without significant modifications. Wing with microtrichia virtually absent from entire surface; R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1040,1065,1269,1283]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">2+3</subScript>
originating well beyond distal margin of discal cell, R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[427,435,1315,1329]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">4</subScript>
absent, crossvein r-m present, short; discal cell small; M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1108,1116,1315,1329]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">1</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1201,1209,1315,1329]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">3</subScript>
faint beyond bases at discal cell, no veins reaching posterior margin of wing; about distal third of A 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1092,1100,1360,1374]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">1</subScript>
faint.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,314,1843]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
Abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[333,405,1390,1416]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–10" captionStartId="6.[151,269,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,245,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-41@6.[151,1436,194,1882]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 8–10. Panamamyia silbergliedi, gen. nov., sp. nov., male holotype. 8, dorsal view. 9, lateral view. 10, head and antennae, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107276" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107276/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) approximately two times longer than wide, very gradually tapering posteriorly from second segment, and flattened dorsally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,314,1843]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis box="[198,294,1475,1500]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Female.</emphasis>
Differs from male as follows: Head (
<figureCitation box="[746,885,1475,1501]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–13" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1925,1949]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-39@7.[151,1436,194,1901]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 11–13. Panamamyia silbergliedi, gen. nov., sp. nov., female paratype. 11, dorsal view. 12, lateral view. 13, dorsolateral view of head and antennae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107280" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107280/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Figs. 11, 13</figureCitation>
) with eyes smaller than male, strongly dichoptic, upper frons parallel-sided, 0.44 width of head, with medial elevated ridge in lower part that is very narrowly grooved medially (
<figureCitation box="[474,569,1561,1587]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–13" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1925,1949]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-39@7.[151,1436,194,1901]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 11–13. Panamamyia silbergliedi, gen. nov., sp. nov., female paratype. 11, dorsal view. 12, lateral view. 13, dorsolateral view of head and antennae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107280" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107280/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
); small depressions present on either side of this ridge, with small protuberances on each side of depressions; lower frons and face with conical projection more developed than in male. Gena and occiput visible in lateral view, forming a broad border on lower and posterior margins of eye that is sharply margined above and more rounded ventrally. Eye bare, ommatidia uniform in size, small.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,314,1843]" box="[198,1222,1731,1757]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
Abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[330,413,1731,1757]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–13" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1925,1949]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-39@7.[151,1436,194,1901]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 11–13. Panamamyia silbergliedi, gen. nov., sp. nov., female paratype. 11, dorsal view. 12, lateral view. 13, dorsolateral view of head and antennae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107280" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107280/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
) slightly more strongly tapering posteriorly. Cercus two-segmented.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="32" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,314,1843]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,339,1773,1799]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Etymology.</emphasis>
This genus is named after 
<collectingCountry box="[662,758,1774,1800]" name="Panama" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Panama</collectingCountry>
, the only country from which specimens are known; feminine in gender.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
